e. It seems like compileScala depends on compileJava, and vice versa, for both Scala and Java classes. I'll look closer into how Gradle handles this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing Scala and Java dependencies**\\n\\nI’m going through older documents, and it says the Scala plugin assumes that Scala sources may depend on Java. So, the compileJava task is set up to depend on compileScala, which could create issues if Scala relies on Java. I think I could eliminate the Scala support object and consider creating a Java class that acts like a Scala object. To avoid compilation order issues, I might need a Scala object method that returns Java classes fully qualified. I’ll need to work this through carefully!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering support object implementation**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how to create a support object that doesn't statically type Java classes, perhaps by returning `Object`. For example, if I define `val publicFieldHolder: AnyRef = create`, but that requires the Java class at runtime, which might complicate things. I could define this in Java only, or even have the support object use a Java class like `java.awt.Point`. I need to find a way to return a string while handling the necessary field correctly. This is a bit tricky!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_U1HBnX4wpd6JrlQDjVzH9VCO|fc_0f85615d283352ba0169fa26db78508192b32d71d0de82bd59", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rm -rf tests/src/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/src/main/java"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"rm -rf tests/src/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/src/main/java\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 240, "output": 1320, "cacheRead": 31744, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 33304, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778